node.text:
I've received many direct messages, comments and emails with your questions about forgiveness, like:
- What does forgiveness look like in relationships that can’t be restored?
- What do you do when you love the person, but you don’t trust the person?
- How do I receive someone else’s forgiveness?
I'm answering all of these questions and more in this conversation. Watch the video and find out more about "Forgiving What You Can't Forget" at www.forgivingwhatyoucantforget.com ❤️

node.title: The Questions You’ve Always Wanted to Ask About Forgiveness

node.text: If forgiveness has ever felt unfair or impossible for you, this 30 minute conversation will be well worth your time.

This informative conversation with @loswhit is what so many of you have been asking for. I’m so proud of Carlos’ bravery in telling us about the season of brokenness in his marriage and how God drew his heart back. 
Plus, we answer some of your questions as well! 
For more information about his new book go to EnterWild.com 🎉

node.text:
Salty air. Wind blown hair. Praise songs blaring. Friends who are caring. Rope swing Fails. Adventure trails. Swimming with pigs and sunrise pics. Creatures in the deep blue sea. But it was the laughter we shared  that was the greatest gift of all to me. 

Always remember that just because some things in your life might feel terrifyingly uncertain, doesn’t mean it’s going to turn out terrible. It could just mean that some of the best parts are still unwritten. ❤️

Hey you… you can do this. This too shall pass. But don’t just get through this part. Find the beauty. Bring it inside. 

And say, “I’m so much stronger than I ever dreamed possible.  And when I’m not, God still is. Thank you, God. Help me, God. Show me, God.” 

And then sleep knowing He loves you. He’s got you. He knows…

node.text:
Part of learning to see beautiful again is recognizing that a hard season doesn’t have to be full of only hard days. 

There’s still beauty to be found in the mix of it all. There’s still joy to be found in the midst of it all. There’s still peace to be found in the middle of it all. 

And there are still so many reasons to treasure life and thank God. 

Lets remind one another daily that just because we’ve been hurt doesn’t mean we have to live hurt. 

If someone you know could use this reminder, my new devotional “Seeing Beautiful Again” is available in bookstores or by clicking the link in my profile. 

Also, @giveyterk makes me smile everyday... and has given me a few new grey hairs too! 😂 He’s a cavapoo from @picture_perfect_puppy - the sweetest people with the cutest pups! ❤️

What if you are living a slow-working miracle, sweet friend? 

There are a few times in my life where I’ve seen dramatic moves by God happen quick enough for me to say, “Wow, look what God is doing!” But most of the time, it’s thousands of little shifts so slight that the dailiness of His work doesn’t register in real time.

My new linen hardcover book, Seeing Beautiful Again: 50 Devotions to Find Redemption in Every Part of Your Story, will help you watch for God’s breathtaking goodness right where you are. Because in the middle of the pain you didn’t cause, the change you didn’t want, the reality you didn’t know was coming ... your life can still be beautiful.

The most important voice we need to hear to instruct us on racism and injustice is the voice of Jesus. In Matthew 22:37-40 we hear Jesus answer the Pharisees' question of what is the greatest commandment.

Jesus says, “You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind. This is the great and first commandment. And a second is like it: You shall love your neighbor as yourself. On these two commandments depend all the Law and the Prophets.”⁣

Love the Lord your God. ⁣
Love your neighbor.

Our love of God requires and compels us to love our neighbor. A love of God without a love of our neighbor is a fractured love of God to begin with. Jesus points us to the Old Testament prophets.⁣

One of the most helpful places for us to start is Micah 6:8.⁣

The Prophet Micah defends those being oppressed by calling us to walk humbly with God, do justice, and love mercy. ⁣

✨ Walk Humbly: Imagine walking hand in hand in intimacy with a father. As a child, when we walk in the shadow of our parents hand in hand, we are humbled by their presence, and we live and act as a result of that humility. ⁣

✨ Do Justice: The Hebrew word for justice is “mishpat” and it deals with a legal decision. This speaks of having systems and structures that are not morally bankrupt but reflect the righteous justice of God.⁣

✨ Love Mercy: Because we have experienced extravagant and undeserved mercy, we should flow with extravagant mercy onto others, even if it is undeserved.⁣
⁣
Jesus teaches us that these three characteristics that are mentioned in Micah 6:8 should be embodied and reflected in the lives of Christians as we relate to our neighbors. ⁣
⁣
Who is our neighbor? Every image bearer of God - all of humanity. As Christ followers, we love God with every ounce of our being and we are then sent out to love our neighbors to be a reflection of the love, mercy and justice of God. ⁣
⁣
Jesus is telling His people today to walk humbly, do justice, love mercy and love all of humanity. Will we listen to His voice and instruction? ⁣
⁣
-Joel @muddamalle, Proverbs 31 Ministries Theological Director #p31injusticeandracism
